<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What causes structural unemployment?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Temporary layoffs during economic downturns</option>
            <option letter="b">Workers voluntarily changing jobs</option>
            <option letter="c">Mismatch between worker skills and job requirements</option>
            <option letter="d">Seasonal changes in employment</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>Structural unemployment occurs when there is a fundamental mismatch between workers' skills and the skills required for available jobs, often due to technological change or industry shifts.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>In the circular flow model, what is an example of an injection?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Savings by households</option>
            <option letter="b">Investment spending by firms</option>
            <option letter="c">Tax payments</option>
            <option letter="d">Imports</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Investment spending by firms is an injection into the circular flow as it represents new spending entering the economy. Other injections include government spending and exports.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which group typically benefits from unexpected inflation?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Retirees living on fixed pensions</option>
            <option letter="b">Borrowers with fixed-rate loans</option>
            <option letter="c">Lenders with fixed-rate loans</option>
            <option letter="d">People with large cash savings</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Borrowers with fixed-rate loans benefit from unexpected inflation because they repay their loans with money that is worth less in real terms, while the nominal payment remains the same.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to the Short-Run Aggregate Supply curve when energy prices increase significantly?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Shifts right</option>
            <option letter="b">Shifts left</option>
            <option letter="c">Moves along the curve</option>
            <option letter="d">Becomes more elastic</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>An increase in energy prices raises production costs for firms, causing the Short-Run Aggregate Supply curve to shift left as firms produce less output at each price level.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
